It is recommended to have at least one or two rest days per week. 

During rest days, it is important to still stay active, but avoid any heavy lifting or intense exercise.

Being active doesn’t mean sweaty cardio

Benefits of progressive overload (perfect for TRIM VIP clients to incorporate)

Progressive overload means gradually increasing the weight or resistance used in your exercises over time or during a set.

Here are some benefits of progressive load weight training:

1️⃣Builds muscle:

When you progressively overload your muscles with heavier weights, it forces them to adapt and grow stronger. This can help increase muscle mass and definition.

2️⃣Increases strength: 

As your muscles grow stronger, you’ll be able to lift heavier weights, which can improve your overall strength and power.

3️⃣Prevents plateaus: 

If you keep lifting the same weight over and over again, your muscles will eventually adapt and stop growing. Progressive overload helps prevent this by continuously challenging your muscles with heavier weights.

4️⃣Improves bone density:

Weight-bearing exercises like progressive load weight training can help improve bone density and reduce the risk of osteoporosis.

5️⃣Boosts metabolism: 

Strength training in general can help boost your metabolism, but progressive overload can be particularly effective. When you lift heavier weights, your body has to work harder to recover, which can increase your calorie burn both during and after your workout.

Overall, progressive load weight training can be a great way to build strength, increase muscle mass, and improve overall fitness. However, it’s important to start with a weight that is appropriate for your fitness level and gradually increase the weight over time.

🚨Benefits of Activation warm ups🚨 

It’s important to do activation warm-ups before lifting because they help to prepare your muscles and nervous system for the upcoming workout, which will improve your performance and reduce the risk of injury.

How???

When your muscles are properly activated, they’re better prepared to produce force and power during your TRIM boot camp workout. This can help you lift more weight or perform more reps, leading to greater gains over time.

2️⃣ Reduce the risk of injury: 

By getting your muscles firing properly, you can also reduce the likelihood of compensations or imbalances that can lead to pain or injury

3️⃣ Improve your mind-muscle connection: 

Activation warm-ups can help you to establish a better mind-muscle connection….which means you’re able to control the specific muscles you’re targeting during your TRIM Boot Camp workout.

Benefits of progressive overload (perfect for TRIM VIP clients to incorporate)

Progressive overload means gradually increasing the weight or resistance used in your exercises over time or during a set.

Here are some benefits of progressive load weight training:

1️⃣Builds muscle:

When you progressively overload your muscles with heavier weights, it forces them to adapt and grow stronger. This can help increase muscle mass and definition.

2️⃣Increases strength: 

As your muscles grow stronger, you’ll be able to lift heavier weights, which can improve your overall strength and power.

3️⃣Prevents plateaus: 

If you keep lifting the same weight over and over again, your muscles will eventually adapt and stop growing. Progressive overload helps prevent this by continuously challenging your muscles with heavier weights.

4️⃣Improves bone density:

Weight-bearing exercises like progressive load weight training can help improve bone density and reduce the risk of osteoporosis.

5️⃣Boosts metabolism: 

Strength training in general can help boost your metabolism, but progressive overload can be particularly effective. When you lift heavier weights, your body has to work harder to recover, which can increase your calorie burn both during and after your workout.

Overall, progressive load weight training can be a great way to build strength, increase muscle mass, and improve overall fitness. However, it’s important to start with a weight that is appropriate for your fitness level and gradually increase the weight over time.

🚨This is NOT intermittent fasting 🚨
 Allowing your body to digest for a full 10-12 hours before eating again the next day can help improve your metabolism in several ways  An easy way to do this is stop eating an hour or 2 before bed, and not eating as soon as you get up.  Drink water for the first hour of being awake before breakfast.  The majority of the 12 hours will be before bed and while you are sleeping.  
You need to fast longer than 10-12 hours to do true intermittent fasting. The first 10-12 hours is PURE digestion. 
Why it’s beneficial:  
1. Improved insulin sensitivity: When you digest for an extended period, your body becomes more sensitive to insulin, which is the hormone responsible for regulating blood sugar levels. This increased sensitivity can help improve your metabolism and make it easier for your body to use glucose for energy. 
2. Increased growth hormone: Letting your body digest for the proper amount of time can also stimulate the production of growth hormone, which is important for maintaining muscle mass and improving metabolism. Growth hormone can help increase the rate at which your body burns calories, leading to a faster metabolism. 
3. Reduced inflammation: Eating too frequently can cause chronic inflammation in the body, which can slow down your metabolism. By giving your body a break from food for 12 hours, you may be able to reduce inflammation and improve your metabolism.

Examples: stop eating at 8pm and eat breakfast at 8am.

Why having a goal weight range is better than having a goal weight! 👏

There aren’t many things in life that are exact, and your goal weight shouldn’t be any different. It’s difficult to live a balanced life when you’re obsessed with a specific number you have in your head. Having a goal weight range is a healthier way to look at it. 💯 Your goal weight range may be a 10-15 lb. range and guess what? You can be healthy at the lower end OR the higher end! 🙌

When you’re determining your goal weight range, do so from a healthy state of mind, and don’t allow your brain to convince you to “keep going” when you get close to the lower end of that range. As you near the lower end, it’s important to check in with yourself and check your nutrition. 

If you find yourself saying, “I’m here now so I’ll just keep going”, it’s important for you to be aware of this: You’re thinking from the wrong place in your brain. 

Having a goal weight range gives you some freedom without taking it too far either way. 💃

Emotional eating can be a challenging habit to break, but one strategy that can help is tracking your food and macros. By keeping track of what you eat and how much, you can gain insight into your eating patterns and identify triggers for emotional eating.

Tracking your macros also helps ensure you’re getting the right balance of nutrients to support your health and wellbeing. When you focus on getting enough protein, healthy fats, and complex carbohydrates, you’ll feel fuller for longer and less likely to reach for unhealthy snacks.

But, perhaps the most significant benefit of tracking your food and macros is that it can help you develop a more mindful relationship with food 📣📣📣📣📣.

 When you’re aware of what you’re eating and why, you can start to make conscious choices that align with your goals and values. You can also learn to recognize when you’re eating out of boredom, stress, or other emotional triggers, and find healthier ways to cope with those feelings.

I received some inquiries about the lat pulldown machine and how to use different grips to isolate and engage different muscles. So let’s get into it! 

1️⃣ Overhand Wide Grip: This is the classic grip that people often think of when it comes to lat pulldowns. It’s a wide, overhand (palms facing forward) grip that focuses on the broadest part of your back - the latissimus dorsi. It also engages your teres major and your posterior deltoids. 

2️⃣ Close Grip Overhand: By narrowing your grip (still overhand) and bringing your hands closer together, you’re targeting more of the middle back. This includes muscles like your rhomboids and your middle and lower trapezius, while still working your lats and posterior deltoids.

3️⃣ Underhand Close Grip: Switching your grip to underhand (palms facing you) and keeping it close works the muscles in a different way. This grip puts more emphasis on your lower lats and also significantly involves your biceps, which makes it a great compound movement.

Remember, variety is key in any workout program and TRIM encourages you to explore these different grips. Always maintain good form and control the weight through the full range of motion.

Try these variations in your next back workout, and let me know how it goes! 💯✨

Deep breathing isn’t just for yoga or calming the mind, it’s also the key to working your deep core effectively. 

When we say “deep core,” we mean those innermost muscles like the transverse abdominals, not just the visible ‘six-pack’ muscles. These deep muscles provide stability, support your spine, and are crucial for overall strength.

The secret to engaging them? Deep breathing! 🌬️

When you breathe deeply, fully expanding your lungs, you naturally engage these muscles. Plus, consciously focusing on your breath during workouts can help you tap into this deeper level of strength. 

Next time you’re in a workout, pay attention to your breath. Inhale, expand, and as you exhale, envision pulling your belly button toward your spine. Feel that? That’s your deep core at work! 

Remember, fitness isn’t just about the big, noticeable movements. It’s also about the subtle ones that lay a strong foundation.

Keep breathing, keep moving, and keep shining, TRIM squad! 🌟

🔥 Why the Vacuum Hold is Your Secret Weapon for a Stronger Core 🔥

A powerful core exercise often overlooked in traditional workout routines is the vacuum hold, a move that deeply targets the transverse abdominis (TVA), your deepest abdominal muscle. Here’s why it’s a game-changer:

1️⃣ Strengthens the Deep Core: The TVA acts like a natural weightlifting belt, stabilizing your lower back and pelvis. It’s crucial for preventing injuries and maintaining good posture. Regular vacuum holds help to strengthen this muscle, improving your overall core stability and strength.

2️⃣ Improves Posture and Supports Spinal Health: A strong TVA results in a tighter, flatter stomach and also contributes to a healthy, upright posture. This not only helps you stand tall but also alleviates pressure on the spine.

3️⃣ Enhances Breathing and Diaphragm Function: The vacuum hold requires you to focus on your breathing, which in turn strengthens your diaphragm, improving lung function and oxygen supply to your muscles.

4️⃣ Aids in Waist Trimming: The vacuum hold exercise has the fantastic side effect of helping to sculpt and trim the waistline. Over time, regular engagement of the TVA can help to ‘pull in’ the waist, giving you a more defined midsection.

Remember, as with all exercises, the key to reaping the benefits of the vacuum hold is consistency and correct form. Always prioritize quality over quantity.

Start incorporating the vacuum hold into your workout routine, and let’s build a stronger core together, TRIM Tribe! 💪

I have been so excited about this new feature in the @trim_bootcamp app.

I understood why alcohol needed to be a fat or carb in other trackers to not mess up macros and to be calculated correctly, but honestly, I couldn’t get onboard with that.

Alcohol is its own macro that is 7kcal per gram.

Most trackers don’t track alcohol as its own macro, so to get calories correct, you do need to find another macro to place it with. 

My issue with that was that a client of mine could have 3 vodka sodas, and their carbs look great! But, in reality , they didn’t get those carbs in.

So I said…we are a carb cycling program, we have to fix this. I need my clients to hit their true carbs and macros. 

And with that, we developed our tracker to have alcohol as its own macro.

If you aren’t in the TRIM app and track alcohol as a fat or carb, don’t worry…it’s not that it’s wrong, it’s the work around.

But I do ask you to be aware that if you track alcohol as a fat or carb, your body is not truly hitting numbers.

In TRIM, we have improved the way we track macros.

Not only for alcohol, but also food.

Teaser for upcoming post: our tracker tracks the calories you actually absorb, not what the label necessarily says 🤯.
